nav

Class NavData

  • java.lang.Object
    • nav.NavData

  • public class NavData
extends java.lang.Object
    Defines the storage of all relevant geo data for routing (i.e. topology, roads). All data is loaded into memory. The data contains three types of objects:
    • links: road segments from crossing to crossing. A link has certain driving properties (i.e. max. speed, road type), that are relevant for routing. Links are parts of larger objects called domains that hold the links' geometries.
    • crossings: points in the road network where a driver can make a driving decision. Crossings are endpoints of links.
    • domains: roads in the original meaning. A road may go across crossings thus may consist of multiple links. A domain hold a name and a geometry.
    Author:
    Jörg Roth (Joerg.Roth@th-nuernberg.de)

      • getMaxSpeedKMperHours

        public int getMaxSpeedKMperHours(int linkID)
        For a link: what is the maximum speed as a result of an explicit speed limit; returns 0 if there is no speed limit. Note that speed limits are only indicated, if they are not obvious accordings to the LSI classification. As an example: the speed limit for roads in German cities is 50km/h. For any of these roads, this method returns 0. Only if the speed is limited to, e.g. 30km/h, this value is returned.

      • getReverseLink

        public int getReverseLink(int linkIndex)
        For a link: ID of the reverse link. This is the link that reverses start and end crossing and goes through the geometry points in reverse order. Note: even though for every link there is a reverse link, very often this link is not drivable, e.g. on highways.
